<br>
Take the classic &quot;Nazi at the door&quot; example. You're hiding Jews from the Nazis in your home. They come to your door and ask, &quot;are you hiding Jews in your home?&quot; Under Kant's views, it would be considered ethically wrong to lie to the Nazis and say that you were not hiding the Jews. To hand them over would be right. I like to think Kant wasn't much of a &quot;people person.&quot; <br>
<br>
Now, Mill on the other hand, he thinks that to do what would be best for the most people would be the way to go. So Mill would not hand over the Jews because it would save all their lives, vs. lying to a few Nazis.<br>
<br>
Seems kind of cut-and-dry, doesn't it?<br>
<br>
Take this other example though...a series of terrible murders are committed in a small town. Suppose you were a policeman in this small town, and you know that to catch the criminal who did it and prosecute him would bring amazing relief and happiness to the people of the town. Suppose also, that you *know* no more murders will be committed by the criminal in the town, that his spree is done. However, you also know that you will never catch the actual criminal. There is one homeless man in the town, named Homeless Bob. Homeless Bob is alone in the world, no family, no friends, not even a dog. Suppose you, as a policeman, could pin these murders on Homeless Bob, with undeniable evidence, never get caught, and only you would know the truth. <br>
<br>
Mill would say go for it, prosecuting Homeless Bob for the murders, even though he is an innocent, would bring greater relief to a greater amount of people than not prosecuting him.<br>
<br>
Kant would say absolutely not, as an innocent, Bob should not be prosecuted no matter how happy it would make the townspeople to blame the murders on somebody.<br>
<br>
Kant believes that you must never treat people as a means to an end, but always as an end in themselves. To do otherwise is to dehumanize them. Mill doesn't have a problem with making people means to an end.<br>
<br>
So you see, there's two sides to this coin. They both have their applications, but it is not black and white which is better.<br>
